                    GROUP THEORY
============================================================

This file is an educational guide on group theory, 
structured in two complementary formats:

Classical Presentation (Sections 1-4)
Structure: Defines a group as a set with a binary operation 
satisfying closure, associativity, identity, and inverse 
axioms

Examples: Integer addition, nonzero reals under 
multiplication, permutation groups, dihedral symmetry
groups

Pillars: Group actions, homomorphisms, classification of 
finite simple groups, and representation theory

Applications: Physics (gauge symmetry), chemistry 
(molecular symmetry), computer science, cryptography, and 
pure mathematics

RDG-Compatible Tri-Mode Form (Sections A-E)
The second half reframes group theory using a custom 
SID-PED-RDG decomposition:

SID (Structural): Typed spaces and closure rules
PED (Operational): Operations, morphisms, and dynamics—
including homomorphisms, actions, and representations

RDG (Relational Discovery Geometry): Geometric 
interpretation of orbits, stabilizers, kernels, and 
spectral structure

This tri-mode lens emphasizes that group theory encodes 
symmetry across three dimensions: structural 
foundations, operational mechanisms, and geometric/
relational content.

The file essentially serves as both a standard 
mathematical reference and a demonstration of how 
classical algebraic concepts can be reinterpreted 
through the RDG framework used elsewhere in the 
Domain-papers repository.

